        <section ids="test-plan-and-results" names="test\ plan\ and\ results">
            <title>Test plan and results</title>
            <paragraph>We just want to test the performance of the drogon framework, so we want to simplify the controller’s processing as much as possible. We only do an HttpSimpleController and register it on the <emphasis>/benchmark</emphasis> path. The controller returns <emphasis>&lt;p&gt;Hello, world!&lt;/p&gt;</emphasis> for any request. Set the number of drogon threads to 16. The processing function is as follows and you can find the source code at the <emphasis>drogon/examples/benchmark</emphasis> path:</paragraph>
            <literal_block highlight_args="{}" language="cpp" linenos="False" xml:space="preserve">void BenchmarkCtrl::asyncHandleHttpRequest(const HttpRequestPtr &amp;req, std::function&lt;void (const HttpResponsePtr &amp;)&gt; &amp;&amp;callback)
{
    //write your application logic here
    auto resp = HttpResponse::newHttpResponse();
    resp-&gt;setBody("&lt;p&gt;Hello, world!&lt;/p&gt;");
    resp-&gt;setExpiredTime(0);
    callback(resp);
}</literal_block>
            <paragraph>For comparison, I chose nginx for comparison testing, wrote a <emphasis>hello_world_module</emphasis>, and compiled it with the nginx source. The nginx worker_processes parameter is set to 16.</paragraph>
            <paragraph>The test tool is <emphasis>httpress</emphasis>, a good performance HTTP stress test tool.</paragraph>
